content.description: Crux is right off the ground.  Small crimps and small side pulls with slim feet.  There is a 2 finger sized flake sticking out at about 12 feet for left hand.  The upper half is sustained 5.8 with slopers and side pulls.
content.protection: Thin wires, cams, and ball nuts.
content.location: Tinfoil climbs the middle-left of the northside face of the large free standing block that is just 10 yards SW of the climbing route State Line Stout. The Cobra bouldering routes can found on this same block but around the corner to the climbers right and on the SW facet.  This climb could easily be a High Ball bouldering route as well..

content.description: I'm sure someone has climbed it before me, but I thought I'd add it since it's not there. Face to the left of skillet dinner. You can use the arete, but can't go inside the crack. See picture for the route.
content.protection: I didn't lead it, but there is clearly a lot of places for pro.
content.location: Grab the big jug to the top right and then go straight up. The crux is halfway through. Grab the half-moon indentation, fix your feet, and reach for the next horizontal crack. One big move after that to go to the final horizontal crack and then you are at the top. Sadly, nowhere to rest, so you have to keep going.

content.description: Climbs the steepest section with good holds. Led on gear in the 90's.
content.location: Following some of the steepest section, directly through the crashing wave to the top.

content.description: Corner splittie with many feratures inside little mini buttress.
content.protection: Cams and nuts of most common sizes.
content.location: Skillet Creek bouldering area hidden in isolated south eastern corner of DLSTP.  Found on large buttress about 3/4 along the distinct but little rocky ridge that makes up Skillet Creek area if walking SW direction from River Boulder.

content.description:
Historically this boulder has many variations (problems) on it. They were never named or graded. Climbs range from V0-V6. This is one of the  more obvious lines we saw on this boulder. 

  This problem is on the riverside of the boulder. Start in the middle of the boulder on good holds. Heel hook and make move to good undercling. Make a huge move out right to gain jug, make a few move big moves to finish it up on the arete
content.location: riverside of smaller overhanding boulder. Left and around the corner of River Boulder 1.

content.description:
Historically this boulder has many variations (problems) on it. They were never named or graded. Climbs ranged from V0-V6. This is one of the  more obvious lines we saw on this boulder. 

  There are 2 variations to start this problem out. 

  1. V3 Start on the far left end of the boulder in the pit. Heel hook and use left hand jug and right hand on sloper. Make a big move and work your way up. 

  2. V2 Start using large undercling rail on the right side of the overhang. Make a large move for the same hold as the start 1.
content.location: To the left of Stateland Stout

content.description: A raw material for further industrial processes.Step up into the alcove.  A burly move to get started up the crack, and another burly move to exit at the top, combined with a few contortions in the middle.
content.protection: Wide gear for the lead, smallish gear for the anchor.
content.location: The acute dihedral to the right of Cast Iron.

content.description:
A great blocky feature on the backside of a tower right in the projects. Start squeezing the face and then find a combination of crimps and compression moves to reach a jug. This route climbs in classic DL style.. a technical and unforgiving sequence leads to easier but more consequential climbing to the top

 Thanks to some new beta from Cody Wheeler, the beginning moves go much easier and keep this thing consistently V1 all the way.
content.location: This climbs the backside of a freestanding tower right across from State Land Stout wall

content.description:
A variation of Leopard Cobra, this line stays on the left arete to the top. With the left hand starting under the low roof and right on a half moon side pull, use tension to reach a rail and a crimp. Find high feet, move up to the jug and top out.

 Not using the detached feet makes the first move more balancey and fun
content.location: Backside of the freestanding tower near state land stout

content.description: Same difficulty all the way up corner climb.  Side pulls along crack line and plenty of foot hold options.
content.location: This route is on the wall to the left of the route Cast Iron.  All this can be found around 3/4 along the little rocky ridge that makes up Skillet Creek area when walking in a SW direction starting at the River Boulder spot and passing State Line Stout route.

content.description: This line is the right variation of Leopard Cobra; a solid climb reminiscent of Special K and the Welcome Crack on the north shore. The technical feet up high and the wall looming close behind make this thing pretty spicy. All the holds are there and the top out is satisfying, so git on it!
content.protection: A couple pads and a spot. The wall is close behind
content.location: On the backside of a freestanding tower near the big overhung wall. Starts above the good feet on the right side of the face.

content.description:
Climb slightly overhanging face on slopers and thin holds.  FA was April 2016.  No repeats yet.  

 Going into the corner has been done subsequently and is V7ish, "Softer than Iron".
content.location: The southern wall of the small amphitheater that makes up the bulk of these climbs.  See photos.

content.description:
The main rock formation on the east side of Skillet Creek.  The lower end is "The River Boulder", where an ancient layer of rock overlays the Baraboo quartzite, similar to the unconformity at the north end of the West Bluff at Devils Lake.  The upper end is "Cast Iron". 

  Although south facing, this area is deep in the woods.
